<LENGTH>
<P>
377 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIDBITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEO SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regulars at Pete's Breakfast House in Ventura have probably noticed some 
carpentry work going on next door. Well, that's part of restaurant owner Pete 
Ransom's preparations for opening a takeout operation specializing in 
cappuccino, espresso and baked goods. 
</P>
<P>
 "We first got the space (a former hair salon) in November, 1993," Ransom said. 
"We didn't jump on the retail idea right away because we wanted to look into 
expanding the restaurant. That wasn't a viable option." 
</P>
<P>
 Aside from the coffees and desserts, the new space will stock jams, jellies, 
T-shirts and other merchandise. "As we get going we'll be open to new ideas 
along the retail line. Knickknack stuff," Ransom said. 
</P>
<P>
 Pete's is located at 2055 E. Main St. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 What happens when two former finance managers with no coffeehouse experience 
buy a coffeehouse? Business percolates. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had a 40% increase in business last month," said Ron Fiducia, co-owner of 
the 6-month-old Coffee Connection in Simi Valley. "About half of that increase 
was from movie-theater traffic." 
</P>
<P>
 Though Fiducia and his partner, Scott Hinton, lacked a restaurant background, 
they had the foresight to open their place next to a 10-plex cinema under 
construction. And when the Edwards Simi Valley Plaza opened a couple of months 
ago, Fiducia and Hinton extended their hours for the nighttime movie crowd. 
</P>
<P>
 Business also hasn't been hurt by the 36-flavor coffee menu or the new patio 
seating. Coffee Connection is located at 1407-X E. Los Angeles Ave. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Entries are being accepted for the Sept. 10 Simi Valley Days Chili Cook-Off, 
sponsored by the Rotary Club of Simi Sunrise. There are three divisions of 
competition -- amateur, commercial (as in restaurants) and International Chili 
Society. 
</P>
<P>
 There is no entry fee in the first two categories and just about anything 
goes. As proof, said cook-off chairman Craig Foster, a contestant last year 
added a touch of wild boar to his dish. 
</P>
<P>
 But for those ICS folks, it's very serious business, with entrants looking to 
make their way up the chili ladder into regional, state, national and 
international competitions. Entry is $10 for those who are already ICS members 
and $40 (which includes a $30 membership) for those who need to join. Call 
527-2272 for more information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
