<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA HILLS; IMPROVEMENTS TO INTERSECTION OKD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has given final approval for major improvements to the 
intersection of Moulton and Alicia parkways. 
</P>
<P>
 The changes that the council approved 3 to 1 at its last meeting will include 
double left-turn lanes and free right-turn lanes in all directions. 
</P>
<P>
 The projected $1.6 million in improvements, planned to begin by the end of the 
year, are expected to help traffic flow smoothly through the busy intersection. 
Cars currently back up during the morning and afternoon rush hours with 
commuters using it for access to the Santa Ana and San Diego freeways. 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor R. Craig Scott and Councilmen Joel T. Lautenschleger and L. Allan 
Songstad Jr. voted for the improvements, saying that waits will be shorter if 
cars don't have to stop when they make a right turn. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Randal J. Bressette voted against the improvements. Councilwoman 
Melody Carruth was absent. 
</P>
<P>
 Bressette said he was concerned about the safety of pedestrians and bicyclists 
who would have to cross the free right-turn lane. He said he felt a right-turn 
arrow might better ensure safety. 
</P>
<P>
 The city and two homeowners' associations next to the intersection are 
discussing the style of retaining walls to be installed after the intersection 
is widened. 
</P>
<P>
 Many of the homeowners in the Crestline and Lomas Laguna developments say they 
favor "green walls," which are covered by vegetation to prevent graffiti 
vandalism. 
</P>
<P>
 But City Engineer Ken Rosenfield said rock walls would be just as pleasing to 
the eye and would not be subject to the damage that could plague the green 
walls' sophisticated irrigation systems. 
</P>
<P>
 Funding for the improvement project comes from fees paid by housing developers 
along the Moulton corridor. 
</P>
<P>
 Moulton Parkway is one of four Orange County streets that have been designated 
for "smart street" improvements, including synchronized traffic signals and 
dedicated turn lanes. Improvements also are planned for where Moulton 
intersects La Paz Road and Oso Parkway.LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
