<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; COUNTY TO REINFORCE NEWPORT BAY SLOPES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 County officials plan to spend $111,000 later this year to repair crumbling 
slopes in Upper Newport Bay Regional Park. 
</P>
<P>
 The slopes are next to Backbay Drive in Newport Beach and began eroding last 
year after heavy rainfall saturated the soil, said William L. Zaun, the 
county's director of public works. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials want to repair the slopes before a major landslide occurs, possibly 
closing Backbay Drive. 
</P>
<P>
 The county is now seeking bids for the job, which will involve installing a 
drainage system in the hillside area. Workers will also compact some of the 
soil to make it stronger, Zaun said. 
</P>
<P>
 Backbay Drive will be closed periodically during construction. Officials hope 
to have the job completed by the end of the year. 
</P>
