<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEL MAR; RACING GOES INTERNATIONAL THIS WEEKEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE DISTEL, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Foreign horses will add an international flavor to the upcoming weekend of 
Grade II stakes races here. 
</P>
<P>
 Sunday's Del Mar Handicap and Monday's Del Mar Derby are replete with foreign 
intrigue, or at least intriguing foreign horses. Only Saturday's Del Mar 
Debutante will not have a foreign entry. 
</P>
<P>
 The Handicap, 1 3/8 miles on the turf for $250,000, had the Irish-bred 
Approach The Bench, the winner of the Grade I Eddie Read Handicap August 7. He 
is owned by John Mulhern, trained by Richard Cross and ridden by Corey 
Nakatani. 
</P>
<P>
 Bobby Frankel-trained Regency will be making his U.S. debut, coming off Group 
II victories in France. His last start was in Deauville on August 11. He will 
be ridden by Kent Desormeaux. 
</P>
<P>
 A third entry with foreign roots could be Stavros Niarchos's Caesour, a 
Kentucky-bred whose nine previous races have been in France. 
</P>
<P>
 He has two victories, a second and a third, all on the turf, where the 
Handicap will be contested. His jockey will be Eddie Delahoussaye. 
</P>
<P>
 Four of the 10 horses invited to Monday's $300,000 Derby, a 1 1/8-mile turf 
race for 3 year olds, have foreign touches. 
</P>
<P>
 Bluegrass Prince, making his U.S. debut, is from the stable of Rodney Rash, 
who also has Triple Crown runner Powis Castle in the field. He has been running 
in England, where he won the Group III Diamond Stakes in June.  
</P>
<P>
 Frankel's Eagle Eyed, owned by Juddmonte Farms, raced in France in 1993, but 
has been at Santa Anita, Golden Gate and Arlington this year. He was winner of 
the Arlington Classic, a Grade II race, under Nakatani. 
</P>
<P>
 Marvin's Faith, Irish-bred, has campaigned strictly in California. He won the 
La Jolla Handicap on August 14 by a nose over Unfinished Symph, another Derby 
entrant. 
</P>
<P>
 Fumo Di Londra, invited but considered an unlikely entrant, raced in Italy, 
Germany and England before coming to trainer Ron McAnally's stable earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 The only "accent" in Saturday's $250,000 Debutante for 2-year-old fillies will 
be southern. Ten of the 16 entries were bred in Kentucky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
