<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY SESSION TO ADDRESS GANG VIOLENCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gang and youth violence among Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders in the 
West San Gabriel Valley will be discussed this evening at a community meeting 
at Cal State L.A. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 50 people from Alhambra, Rosemead, Monterey Park and surrounding 
areas are expected to attend the free session, from 6:30 to 9:30 p.m. at the 
Roybal Institute Conference Room on campus. Issues include the impact of the 
"three-strikes" legislation that requires life imprisonment for repeat 
offenders and the effect of Proposition 187, which would deny public services 
and education to illegal immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
 The forum is the third in a series of four held by the Gang Violence Bridging 
Project. Previous meetings in East Los Angeles and South-Central Los Angeles 
concentrated on Latino and African American youths. A final conference Nov. 19 
at Cal State L.A. will unite all the groups. 
</P>
<P>
 The free event is open to the public. Information: (213) 343-3770. 
</P>
</TEXT>
